# Acadamark Feature Test Document

This document exercises every authoring feature acadamark currently supports. It serves three purposes: as a smoke test for the parser, as a feature catalog for humans, and as a living example of what acadamark source looks like in practice.

## What runs end-to-end today

These features run from source through to their structured representation as of Slice 3.5:

- All sigil families: `#`, `##`, `###`, `$`, `$$`, `` ` ``, ```` ``` ````.
- Sigil tags with and without the `|` separator.
- Named tags in short form, with and without content.
- All attribute forms: positionals, bracketed lists, boolean flags (`+flag`, `-flag`), ids (`#id`), classes (`.class`), keyword arguments (`key=value`, `key="quoted"`).
- Permissive identifiers: hyphens, colons, dots, slashes mid-identifier (paths, URLs, colon-prefixed ids).
- Markdown coexisting with acadamark constructs in the same document.
- Nested constructs inside named-tag content, as far as boundary detection goes.

## What is exercised here but does not yet render fully

These authoring patterns are valid acadamark source and the parser handles them, but the downstream pieces (interpreter, section-nesting bridge) are not yet built. Sections marked with the **(future pipeline)** annotation are exercising correct authoring patterns whose end-to-end rendering is a future slice.

- Implicit section nesting. The parser produces correctly-shaped tags for `<section>`, `<sub-section>`, `<sub-sub-section>` without explicit closing; the existing `rehype-section-nesting` plugin nests flat section markers correctly; the bridge between them (the interpreter) is not yet built.
- Recursive parsing of named-tag content. Constructs nested inside named-tag content are bounded correctly by the parser, but the inner constructs are part of an opaque content string and not yet structured as child nodes. The recursive-content slice resolves this.

## What is deliberately not exercised

These features are not yet implemented and are not exercised here:

- Multi-line named tags. The parser is single-line through Slice 3.5.
- Long-form DSL tags such as `<csv>...</csv>`. Slice 4.
- The qualifying-tag pattern such as `<table csv | ...>`. Slice 5.

---

## Part 1: Sigil tags

### 1.1. Heading sigils, no attributes

<# Introduction #>

<## Background and motivation ##>

<### A finer subdivision ###>

Features: sigil tags at all three heading levels, no `|` (whole body is opaque content), no attribute parsing.

### 1.2. Heading sigils with attributes

<# #intro | Introduction #>

<## #background .numbered | Background ##>

<### #fine-grain .numbered .reviewed +draft | A finer subdivision ###>

Features: `|` enables attribute parsing, ids via `#`, multiple classes, boolean flags. Without `|` the body is opaque and no attributes are parsed.

### 1.3. Heading sigil with all attribute forms

<# #methods .numbered .reviewed level=primary status="in review" +draft -published | Methods #>

Features: id, multiple classes, unquoted keyword, quoted keyword (with embedded space), positive flag, negative flag, all in one tag.

### 1.4. Inline math, no `|`

The Pythagorean identity <$ a^2 + b^2 = c^2 $> holds for right triangles.

A complex expression with embedded special characters: <$ \frac{-b \pm \sqrt{b^2 - 4ac}}{2a} $>.

Features: inline math sigil, opaque content (no attribute parsing), backslashes and braces preserved verbatim.

### 1.5. Display math, no `|`

The fundamental theorem of calculus:

<$$ \int_a^b f'(x)\,dx = f(b) - f(a) $$>

A more complex display:

<$$ \sum_{n=1}^{\infty} \frac{1}{n^2} = \frac{\pi^2}{6} $$>

Features: display math sigil, opaque content, longer expressions, summation notation.

### 1.6. Math sigils with attributes

<$ #pythagoras .important | a^2 + b^2 = c^2 $>

<$$ #euler-identity .featured number=eq:1 | e^{i\pi} + 1 = 0 $$>

Features: id, classes, and kwargs on math sigils; the `|` separates attributes from the math expression itself.

### 1.7. Inline code, no `|`

To declare a constant in JavaScript, write <` const x = 1 `>. The arrow function form is <` (x) => x * 2 `>.

Features: inline code sigil, opaque content.

### 1.8. Inline code with attributes

<` #example-1 .highlighted lang=js | const greeting = "hello" `>

Features: id, class, keyword on a code sigil.

### 1.9. Code block sigil, no `|`

<``` function fibonacci(n) { return n < 2 ? n : fibonacci(n-1) + fibonacci(n-2); } ```>

Features: triple-backtick sigil, opaque content. The parser is single-line through Slice 3.5; multi-line code block content is a planned future feature.

### 1.10. Code block sigil with attributes

<``` #fib-example .demo lang=js +runnable | function add(a, b) { return a + b; } ```>

Features: triple-backtick sigil with id, class, keyword, and flag.

---

## Part 2: Named tags — attribute forms

This part exercises every attribute form the parser recognizes, using simple named tags that don't carry semantic meaning at this stage.

### 2.1. Single positional

<cite jones2024>

### 2.2. Multiple positionals

<cite jones2024 smith2023 perez2019>

Features: positional arguments are space-separated and accumulate into the `positional` array.

### 2.3. Bracketed list as a single positional

<cite [jones2024, smith2023, perez2019]>

Features: bracketed list is one positional whose value is the array of items. Compare with 2.2 above (multiple positionals) — same surface tokens, different parse.

### 2.4. Quoted items in a bracketed list

<cite ["author with spaces, comma", jones2024, "another"]>

Features: list items may be quoted, allowing spaces and commas inside.

### 2.5. Id

<section #methods>

Features: `#id` form.

### 2.6. Single class

<aside .footnote>

### 2.7. Multiple classes

<div .container .featured .dark-mode>

Features: classes accumulate into the `classes` array.

### 2.8. Unquoted keyword

<figure align=right>

### 2.9. Quoted keyword (single quotes)

<figure caption='An adult African elephant'>

### 2.10. Quoted keyword (double quotes)

<figure caption="An adult African elephant, photographed in Tanzania">

Features: either quote type works; commas and spaces are preserved inside.

### 2.11. Positive flag

<figure +wrap>

### 2.12. Negative flag

<figure -published>

### 2.13. Multiple flags

<cite jones2024 +link +preview -inline>

### 2.14. All attribute forms in one tag

<figure src=elephant.jpg #adult-elephant .photo .featured align=right caption="An adult elephant" +wrap -draft>

Features: positional (`src`'s value before realizing this is a kwarg — actually `src=elephant.jpg` is a kwarg, not a positional), id, multiple classes, multiple kwargs (one quoted), positive flag, negative flag. Note: order is free, this happens to put kwargs first and flags last for readability.

### 2.15. Attribute order is free

<figure +wrap .photo src=elephant.jpg .featured align=right -draft #adult #adult-elephant>

Features: same attributes as 2.14, in shuffled order. The id appearing twice (`#adult` then `#adult-elephant`) takes the last value per the spec — implementation may warn.

---

## Part 3: Named tags — content forms

### 3.1. No content

<cite jones2024>

Features: no `|`, no closing tag, tag has no content.

### 3.2. Short-form content

<a https://example.com | Example>

<em | important>

<strong | very important>

Features: `|` introduces content; the `>` after content closes the tag.

### 3.3. Content containing punctuation

<aside | A note with semicolons; em-dashes — and ellipses…>

Features: most punctuation passes through transparently in content.

### 3.4. Content containing nested constructs (boundary detection)

<aside | See the equation <$ E = mc^2 $> for the famous formula.>

<aside | The function <` factorial(n) `> computes a factorial.>

<aside | Refer to <ref fig:elephant> for the photograph.>

<figure src=elephant.jpg | An adult elephant. See also <ref fig:calf>.>

Features: nested sigil tags and nested named tags inside named-tag content. The parser's rule-B depth tracking (extended in Slice 3.5 to recognize `$`, `` ` `` as well as `#`) ensures the outer `>` doesn't false-close. **(future pipeline: at Slice 3.5 the inner constructs are part of the outer tag's opaque content string; recursive-content parsing turns them into structured child nodes in a future slice.)**

### 3.5. Content with `<` that does not open a construct

<aside | The condition a < b implies a != b.>

<aside | Compare 5 < 10 and 10 < 100.>

Features: `<` followed by a non-tag-starting character (space, digit) is treated as literal content, not as a nested-construct opener. This is the rule-B refinement in the spec.

### 3.6. Content with literal `>` requires escaping

<aside | The condition a &gt; b implies a != b.>

Features: a literal `>` in content must be written as `&gt;`, since a bare `>` would close the tag.

---

## Part 4: Permissive identifiers

These exercise the start-and-continue identifier rules introduced in Slice 3.

### 4.1. Hyphenated ids

<section #methods-and-results>

<figure #adult-african-elephant>

### 4.2. Colon in identifiers

<ref #fig:body-cross-section>

<ref #eq:euler-identity>

<ref #thm:fundamental-arithmetic>

Features: `:` is allowed mid-identifier and in start position via the start-and-continue split. This enables the `fig:`, `eq:`, `thm:` namespacing convention.

### 4.3. Dots in identifiers (versions, filenames)

<package version=v1.2.3>

<img src=puppy.jpg>

<img src=elephant.png>

Features: `.` is allowed mid-identifier, so version strings and file extensions don't need quoting.

### 4.4. URLs as positional or keyword values

<a https://example.com/path?query=value | Example>

<a href=https://example.com/path | Example>

<cite-source url=https://doi.org/10.1234/example.5678>

Features: slashes, colons, dots, query strings, and `=` inside query strings are all valid mid-identifier. This allows full URLs — including those with `key=value` query parameters — to appear as bare positionals or keyword values without quoting.

### 4.5. Hyphens in keyword values

<img src=my-photo-large.jpg width=240 height=240>

Features: `-` is allowed in keyword values (after `=`). Note: `-` remains excluded at start position, where it would be parsed as a negative flag.

---

## Part 5: Section-style tags and the implicit-close pattern

Acadamark's most distinctive authoring affordance is implicit closing for section-style tags. A new peer-level section ends the previous one without an explicit closing tag, mirroring LaTeX's `\section{}` and `\subsection{}`. This is what makes acadamark source dramatically easier to type than raw HTML.

**(future pipeline: at Slice 3.5 the parser produces individual `acadamarkTag` nodes for each `<section>`, `<sub-section>`, etc.; the existing `rehype-section-nesting` plugin nests flat section markers correctly; the interpreter that bridges the parser output to the section-nesting plugin is a future slice. The authoring patterns in this part are correct acadamark source today — the structural nesting will be observable end-to-end once the interpreter lands.)**

### 5.1. Flat sections, peer-level

<section #intro | Introduction>

<section #methods | Methods>

<section #results | Results>

<section #discussion | Discussion>

Features: each section uses the short-form `<tag attrs | content>` pattern. No explicit closing required. When the section-nesting bridge is in place, these become four sibling `<section>` elements in the output HTML.

### 5.2. Sections with sub-sections

<section #intro | Introduction>

Some introductory prose.

<sub-section #motivation | Motivation>

The motivation is described here.

<sub-section #related-work | Related Work>

A discussion of related work.

<section #methods | Methods>

The methods section begins, implicitly ending the related-work sub-section *and* the introduction section.

Features: section depth is tracked by the named depth ladder (`section`, `sub-section`, `sub-sub-section`). A new `section` closes any open `sub-section` *and* the previous `section`. A new `sub-section` closes any open `sub-section` but stays inside the current `section`.

### 5.3. Three-deep section nesting

<section #intro | Introduction>

Top-level prose.

<sub-section #background | Background>

<sub-sub-section #history | History>

History prose.

<sub-sub-section #context | Context>

Context prose. This implicitly closes the history sub-sub-section.

<sub-section #scope | Scope>

Scope prose. This implicitly closes the context sub-sub-section *and* the background sub-section's nesting at depth 3.

<section #methods | Methods>

Methods prose. This implicitly closes everything still open at greater depth.

Features: full three-level nesting, with implicit closing at all depths handled by the section-nesting plugin.

### 5.4. Section title vocabulary

<section #intro>
<section-title | Introduction>

Introductory prose follows.

<sub-section #motivation>
<sub-section-title | Motivation>

Motivation prose.

Features: container-role naming (Rule 1 in `notes/layer1-naming.md`). `<section-title>` is the title of a `<section>`; `<sub-section-title>` is the title of a `<sub-section>`. The parent's `|` is omitted when the title is provided as a separate child element rather than as content.

### 5.5. Article title at the top of a document

<article-title | A Theory of Everything>
<article-subtitle | With Special Attention to Edge Cases>

<section #intro | Introduction>

Document body begins.

Features: `<article-title>` and `<article-subtitle>` per Rule 1. These produce custom elements at Layer 1; in render mode they would lower to `<h1>` / `<p class="subtitle">` for browser default styling.

---

## Part 6: Citations and cross-references

These exercise the syntactic forms; the resolution to bibliography entries and figure numbers happens in the citation and cross-ref plugins (Phase 2 of the build plan), not at the parser level.

### 6.1. Single citation

According to <cite jones2024>, the effect is well-documented.

### 6.2. Multiple citations as positionals

The phenomenon is widely studied <cite jones2024 smith2023 perez2019>.

### 6.3. Bracketed-list citation

The phenomenon is widely studied <cite [jones2024, smith2023, perez2019]>.

Features: bracketed list as a single positional. Functionally equivalent to 6.2 in this case, but the bracketed form preserves "this is one citation group" semantics for the interpreter.

### 6.4. Citation with formatting flags

According to <cite jones2024 +link +preview>, the effect is well-documented.

Features: flags on a citation control downstream interpretation (e.g., `+link` requests a hyperlink, `+preview` requests a hover preview).

### 6.5. Cross-reference to a figure

See <ref fig:elephant> for the photograph.

### 6.6. Cross-reference with formatting flags

See <ref fig:elephant +link +preview +title> for the photograph.

Features: flags request the link, the preview, and the figure title in the rendered cross-reference.

### 6.7. Cross-reference to an equation

The result follows from <ref eq:euler-identity>, derived above.

### 6.8. Cross-reference to a section

We discuss this in <ref sec:methods> and revisit it in <ref sec:discussion>.

---

## Part 7: Figures

### 7.1. Figure with positional source

<figure puppy.jpg>

Features: a single positional argument names the source file.

### 7.2. Figure with keyword source and caption

<figure src=elephant.jpg caption="An adult African elephant, photographed in Tanzania.">

### 7.3. Figure with id, classes, and dimensions

<figure src=elephant.jpg #adult-elephant .photo .featured width=600 height=400>

### 7.4. Figure with caption containing nested constructs

<figure src=elephant.jpg #elephant | An adult elephant. See also <ref fig:calf>.>

Features: caption (in content position) contains a nested cross-reference. **(future pipeline: the inner `<ref>` is bounded correctly today; structured as a child node when recursive-content parsing lands.)**

### 7.5. Figure with caption containing math

<figure src=trajectory.png #trajectory | The trajectory follows <$ y = \frac{1}{2}gt^2 $> for free fall.>

Features: nested math sigil inside caption. **(future pipeline: same as 7.4.)**

### 7.6. Figure with caption containing citation

<figure src=elephant.jpg #elephant | An adult African elephant <cite jones2024>.>

Features: nested citation inside caption. **(future pipeline: same as 7.4.)**

### 7.7. Figure with caption containing emphasis and code

<figure src=architecture.png #arch | The *architecture* uses the <` unified `> ecosystem.>

Features: markdown emphasis (`*architecture*`) and a nested inline-code sigil inside caption. **(future pipeline: markdown emphasis inside named-tag content gets parsed when recursive-content is wired through remark.)**

---

## Part 8: Lists

Acadamark allows lists via either standard markdown (the bare idiom) or via the `<list>` tag (when attributes are needed).

### 8.1. Bare markdown list (delegated to remark)

- First item
- Second item
- Third item

Features: standard markdown unordered list. Delegated to remark per the principle in `notes/idioms.md`.

### 8.2. Bare markdown ordered list

1. First step
2. Second step
3. Third step

### 8.3. Bare nested list

- Top-level item
  - Nested item
  - Another nested item
- Second top-level item

### 8.4. Tagged list (when attributes are needed)

<list +ordered #steps .important | Calibrate the apparatus; record the baseline; apply the perturbation; record the response.>

Features: id, class, flag on a list. The `+ordered` flag distinguishes from unordered. The parser is single-line through Slice 3.5; multi-line list content is a planned future feature. **(future pipeline: list content is currently an opaque string; the interpreter handles item-level parsing.)**

---

## Part 9: Markdown coexisting with acadamark

Per the delegation principle, markdown idioms are accepted inline alongside acadamark constructs. The two registers mix freely.

### 9.1. Bold, italic, and links in prose

This paragraph has *emphasized* text, **strong** text, and a [link](https://example.com).

The same paragraph mixed with acadamark: <em | emphasized>, <strong | strong>, and <a https://example.com | link>.

Features: both registers produce equivalent Layer 1 output. Use markdown when sufficient; reach for shorthand when attributes are needed.

### 9.2. Bare math alongside tagged math

The famous formula $E = mc^2$ is also writeable as <$ E = mc^2 $>. The tagged form supports attributes: <$ #mass-energy .featured | E = mc^2 $>.

Features: bare `$x$` is delegated to `remark-math`; tagged `<$x$>` is acadamark. Both produce equivalent semantics; only the tagged form supports attributes.

### 9.3. Bare code spans alongside tagged code sigils

The bare form `code` is delegated to remark. The tagged form <` code `> supports attributes: <` #example .highlighted | const x = 1 `>.

### 9.4. Bare headings alongside heading sigils

# This is a markdown heading

<# #intro | This is an acadamark heading sigil #>

Features: both produce headings at Layer 1. The tagged form supports attributes; the bare form does not. **(future pipeline: bare markdown headings produce flat `<h1>` etc., while sigil headings produce `<section-title>` inside a `<section>` once the interpreter and section-wrapping behavior are settled. See open question in `notes/layer1-naming.md`.)**

---

## Part 10: Edge cases worth exercising

### 10.1. Sigil character inside opaque content

<$ \int x \, dx $> contains no `$` until the closer.

<$ a + $b $> — the inner `$` is just a single dollar; only `$>` (with the matching `>`) closes.

Features: the closer is the sigil character followed by `>`, not just the sigil character. A bare `$` inside content is allowed.

### 10.2. Backtick inside opaque content

<` const s = "hello" `> contains no backticks until the closer.

<``` const a = `template`; ```> — the inner backticks are content; only ` ``` ` followed by `>` closes.

Features: same logic as 10.1, applied to backticks.

### 10.3. Multi-character closer with shorter sigil inside

<$$ x = $1 \cdot y$ $$> — single-`$` runs inside double-`$` content do not close.

Features: the closer must match the opener exactly (same character, same count).

### 10.4. No `|` means no attribute parsing

<# #intro Introduction #>

Features: this parses as a sigil with content `" #intro Introduction "` — the `#intro` is part of the opaque body, not parsed as an id, because there is no `|`.

### 10.5. Consecutive constructs

<cite jones2024><cite smith2023>

<a https://a.com | A><a https://b.com | B>

Features: tags can appear back-to-back with no whitespace.

### 10.6. Construct at end of line with trailing whitespace

<cite jones2024>   

Features: trailing whitespace after `>` is ignored at the parser level.

### 10.7. Tag name with digits and underscores

<h1 | Heading>
<my_custom_tag | content>
<my-custom-tag | content>
<tag123 | content>

Features: tag name pattern is `[a-zA-Z][a-zA-Z0-9_-]*` per the spec.

### 10.8. Empty content

<aside | >

<a https://example.com | >

Features: `|` followed by only whitespace and `>` produces empty content.

---

## Part 11: A small worked document

A sketch of what a real acadamark document looks like, putting many features together.

<article-title | Numerical Estimates of Elephant Reaction Times>
<article-subtitle | A Pilot Study>

<section #intro | Introduction>

Reaction-time studies in megafauna are scarce <cite jones2024 smith2023>. The present work fills this gap by measuring response latencies in *Loxodonta africana* under controlled conditions.

<sub-section #motivation | Motivation>

The fundamental question is whether body size correlates with reaction time, as predicted by <cite perez2019>. The model predicts a relationship of the form <$ \tau \propto m^{1/3} $>, where $\tau$ is reaction time and $m$ is body mass.

<sub-section #related-work | Related Work>

Prior work in this area is reviewed in <ref sec:methods>.

<section #methods | Methods>

We followed the protocol described in <cite jones2024 +link>, with three modifications detailed below.

<figure src=apparatus.jpg #apparatus .featured | The experimental apparatus, as deployed in Tanzania <cite jones2024>.>

Calibration followed the equation:

<$$ #calib-eq | y = \alpha x + \beta + \epsilon $$>

where $\epsilon$ is a Gaussian noise term.

<section #results | Results>

The results are summarized in <ref fig:apparatus>. The fitted relationship matches <ref eq:calib-eq> within experimental uncertainty.

<section #discussion | Discussion>

The implications are several. First, the prediction in <ref sec:motivation> is supported. Second, the data suggest follow-up work is warranted.

Features in this part: article title and subtitle, four top-level sections, two sub-sections in the introduction, citations (single and multiple), cross-references (to figure, equation, and sections), inline math (bare and tagged), display math (tagged with id), figure with caption containing a nested citation, markdown emphasis inside prose. **(future pipeline: the structural nesting and the cross-reference resolution are exercised end-to-end when the interpreter and Phase 2 plugins land.)**

---

## End

If a parser revision causes any section above to fail to parse, that is a regression. If a section parses but produces a different structure than before, that is drift and should be investigated against the spec.

When the recursive-content slice lands, the sections marked **(future pipeline)** for nested-content reasons should be re-validated end-to-end. When the interpreter lands, the section-nesting and citation-resolution sections should be re-validated end-to-end.
